      "writtenOn": "2026-03-09T17:25:53Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e \u003e To reduce the number of compile units. \n\u003e \n\n\u003e meson supports unity builds if you want to reduce the number of build TUs.\nNot interested in debating unit builds in this review.  Happy to discuss them in the appropriate forums (mailing list or discord).\n\n\u003e \n\n\u003e As written this is making a tradeoff with incremental compilation performance which is an quite important for contributors using smaller machines.\n\nHow so?  for this specific case, the usb daemon is dominated by link time.  When I\u0027ve measured in similar scenarios, the duplication of compile between compile units makes multiple compile units worse when LTO is enabled.  I will admit I haven\u0027t measured this specific daemon, but making generalities about a commit doesn\u0027t really help me understand the problem with this commit.  Were you not able to compile it?\n\n\u003e \n\u003e See https://isocpp.github.io/CppCoreGuidelines/CppCoreGuidelines#sf2-a-header-file-must-not-contain-object-definitions-or-non-inline-function-definitions\n\u003e also\n\n\nThis is a class definition, and is allowed by the cpp core guilelines doc you linked.\n\n\"A header file must contain only:.... class definitions\"",
